<section id="fs-id1167793753996" class="section-exercises">
<exercise id="fs-id1167793754000">
<problem id="fs-id1167793754002">
<para id="fs-id1167793754004">The domain of vector field <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is a set of points <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> in a plane, and the range of <emphasis effect="bold">F</emphasis> is a set of <emphasis effect="italics">what</emphasis> in the plane?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167793545479">
<para id="fs-id1167793545482">Vectors</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<para id="fs-id1167793570047">For the following exercises, determine whether the statement is <emphasis effect="italics">true or false</emphasis>.</para><exercise id="fs-id1167793570059">
<problem id="fs-id1167793570061">
<para id="fs-id1167793570064">Vector field <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>〈</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mo>〉</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is a gradient field for both <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>ϕ</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>ϕ</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>100</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167793325793">
<problem id="fs-id1167793325795">
<para id="fs-id1167793325798">Vector field <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>〈</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>〉</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msqrt><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow></m:msqrt></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math> is constant in direction and magnitude on a unit circle.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167793545088">
<para id="fs-id1167793545090">False</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167794121973">
<problem id="fs-id1167794121975">
<para id="fs-id1167794121977">Vector field <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>〈</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>〉</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msqrt><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow></m:msqrt></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math> is neither a radial field nor a rotation.</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<para id="fs-id1167793977437">For the following exercises, describe each vector field by drawing some of its vectors.</para>
<exercise id="fs-id1167793977440">
<problem id="fs-id1167793977442">
<para id="fs-id1167793977444"><emphasis effect="bold">[T]</emphasis> <m:math><m:mrow><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>F</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>i</m:mtext></m:mstyle><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mstyle mathvariant="bold" mathsize="normal"><m:mtext>j</m:mtext></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167793300333"><para id="fs-id1167793300334"><newline/>
<media id="fs-id1167793300337" alt="A visual representation of a vector field in two dimensions. The arrows are larger the further they are from the origin. They stretch away from the origin in a radial pattern.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/CNX_Calc_Figure_16_01_201.jpg"/>
</media></para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167794170760">
<problem id="fs-id1167794170762">
